04360nam a22007455i 9780271036557DE-B159720220524034747.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220524t20212009pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710365577 a10.1515/97802710365572doi  a(DE-B1597)584333  a(OCoLC)1253313036  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aZ658.G7bR63 2009eb 7aLIT0070002bisacsh04a363.310942/090322221 aRobertson, Randy, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCensorship and Conflict in Seventeenth-Century England :bThe Subtle Art of Division /cRandy Robertson. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©2009  a1 online resource (288 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPenn State Series in the History of the Book0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCensorship profoundly affected early modern writing. Censorship and Conflict in Seventeenth-Century England offers a detailed picture of early modern censorship and investigates the pressures that censorship exerted on seventeenth-century authors, printers, and publishers. In the 1600s, Britain witnessed a civil war, the judicial execution of a king, the restoration of his son, and an unremitting struggle among crown, parliament, and people for sovereignty and the right to define "liberty and property." This battle, sometimes subtle, sometimes bloody, entailed a struggle for the control of language and representation. Robertson offers a richly detailed study of this "censorship contest" and of the craft that writers employed to outflank the licensers. He argues that for most parties, victory, not diplomacy or consensus, was the ultimate goal. This book differs from most recent works in analyzing both the mechanics of early modern censorship and the poetics that the licensing system produced-the forms and pressures of self-censorship. Among the issues that Robertson addresses in this book are the workings of the licensing machinery, the designs of art and obliquity under a regime of censorship, and the involutions of authorship attendant on anonymity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aCensorshipxHistoryx17th centuryxEngland. 0aCensorshipxHistoryy17th centuryxEngland. 0aCensorshipzEnglandxHistoryy17th century. 0aEnglish literaturexHistory and criticismxEarly modern, 1500-1700. 0aEnglish literaturexHistory and criticismyEarly modern, 1500-1700. 0aEnglish literatureyEarly modern, 1500-1700xHistory and criticism. 0aPolitics and literaturexHistoryx17th centuryxGreat BritainxEnglandxGreat Britain. 0aPolitics and literaturezGreat BritainxHistoryy17th centuryxEngland. 0aPolitics and literaturezGreat BritainxHistoryy17th century. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Books & Reading.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014z978311074526940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271036557?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271036557423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780271036557/original  a978-3-11-074526-9  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014b2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK